<p>Among electric fish, those that live in freshwater have their generating cells arranged &#8220;in series&#8221;; in saltwater they appear &#8220;in parallel.&#8221;</p>
<p>Seawater conducts better than fresh water, so freshwater fish need to generate a high voltage to overcome the resistance of their medium. Their electricity-producing cells are arranged in series.</p>
<p>Marine fish operate at higher currents but lower voltages, so their electrocytes appear in parallel.</p>
